 1. Introduction to Generative AI - Art of the Possible\textsf{\color{lime} 1. Introduction to Generative AI - Art of the Possible} 1. Introduction to Generative AI - Art of the Possible

 1.a. INTRODUCTION TO GENERATIVE AI\textsf{\color{orange} 1.a. INTRODUCTION TO GENERATIVE AI} 1.a. INTRODUCTION TO GENERATIVE AI

 1.a.i. Overview of ML\textsf{\color{magenta} 1.a.i. Overview of ML} 1.a.i. Overview of ML

  • Generative artificial intelligence(generative AI) is a branch of machine learning (ML).

  • It is concerned with the development of algorithms that can create natural language text, images, code, audio, or videos based on user input.

What is ML?\textsf{\color{cyan}What is ML?}What is ML?

  • ML is training a computer to recognize patterns in historical data to make predictions on new data.

  • A dataset is used to train a model. In this dataset, there are features and labels.
  • The goal is to take the features as inputs and find a formula that predicts the labels, or outputs.
  • The resulting ML algorithms can take new data, recognize patterns in the data, apply the formula, and make predictions about the data.

 Understanding the difference between generative AI and traditional ML\textsf{\color{cyan} Understanding the difference between generative AI and traditional ML} Understanding the difference between generative AI and traditional ML

  • Generative AI is a subset of deep learning because it can adapt models built using deep learning.
  • Deep learning uses the concept of neurons and synapses similar to how our brain is wired.
  • Generative AI is powered by large language models that are pretrained on internet-scale data, and these models are called foundation models (FMs).

The large language models (LLM) or FMs have the ability to predict the next word in a sentence by taking into consideration the position and the context of a word in a sentence. LLMs use this ability to generate new content.

 1.a.ii. Basics of Generative AI\textsf{\color{magenta} 1.a.ii. Basics of Generative AI} 1.a.ii. Basics of Generative AI

 What is generative AI?\textsf{\color{cyan} What is generative AI?} What is generative AI?

  • Generative AI is a type of AI that can create new content, including conversations, stories, images, videos, music, and code.

  • Examples: CodeWhisperer, Create With Alexa

 1.a.iii. Generative AI use cases\textsf{\color{magenta} 1.a.iii. Generative AI use cases} 1.a.iii. Generative AI use cases

  • AWS Inferentia and AWS Trainium are purpose-built ML accelerators that AWS designed from the ground up for training and deploying ultra-large generative AI models.
  • You can use Amazon SageMaker along with the purpose-built AWS Trainium chip to train your own LLMs. Alternatively, choose one of the language models available in SageMaker Jumpstart and retrain it with your own data.
  • Amazon Bedrock is a fully managed service that makes FMs, including Amazon Titan models, from leading AI startups and Amazon available through an API.

 2.a TECHNICAL FOUNDATIONS AND TERMINOLOGY FOR GENERATIVE AI\textsf{\color{orange} 2.a TECHNICAL FOUNDATIONS AND TERMINOLOGY FOR GENERATIVE AI} 2.a TECHNICAL FOUNDATIONS AND TERMINOLOGY FOR GENERATIVE AI

2.a.i Generative AI Fundamentals \textsf{\color{magenta}2.a.i Generative AI Fundamentals }2.a.i Generative AI Fundamentals 

Foundation models\color{cyan} Foundation\ modelsFoundation models

  • An FM is a prebuilt, machine learning (ML) model trained on a large amount of data. The result is a model that can be adapted to a wide range of downstream tasks.
  • FMs are created by taking large amounts of unlabeled data, training a model with that data, and then using that model for a wide range of tasks.

Transformer\color{cyan}TransformerTransformer

  • The transformer architecture is a type of neural network that is efficient, easy to scale and parallelize, and can model interdependence between input and output data.

  • Transformers do not process words sequentially one at a time. Instead, they process the entire input all at once during the learning cycle. This makes the training process highly parallelizable.

  • Transformer models also take advantage of positional information. This provides the model data on the location of words in an input sequence. If you are inputting a sentence, the model captures the importance of each word and the relationships between the words.

  • Position encoders allow models to prevent ambiguous meanings when a word is used in other parts of a sentence. Position encoding allows the transformer model to differentiate the semantic differences between two sentences.

2.a.ii Generative AI in Practice \textsf{\color{magenta}2.a.ii Generative AI in Practice }2.a.ii Generative AI in Practice 

open_in_new
  • Consider the input in this example. You ask the generative AI to complete the following sentence. “A puppy is to dog as kitten is to …”
  • In the first step, the transformer model breaks down the input into smaller parts so that they can be converted to numbers (encoding). These smaller parts are called tokens. Tokens can be words, phrases, or individual characters like a period.
  • After the step of tokenization, the transformer model then encodes these tokens into n-dimensional vectors. These are three-dimensional numerical representations of a word.
  • After all of the tokens have been encoded, the transformer’s decoder uses the vector representation to predict the requested output.
  • A puppy is to dog as kitten is to_______
    • cat 9.2
    • bird 5.5
    • bear 4.7
    • human 3.7
  • Finally, the model outputs its prediction and generates the next word in the sentence. It might complete our sentence as “A puppy is to dog as kitten is to cat.”

2.a.iii Generative AI Context \textsf{\color{magenta}2.a.iii Generative AI Context }2.a.iii Generative AI Context 

Context\color{cyan}ContextContext

Context is a one-on-one session with the model.

It does not persist when you start a new conversation, and there is an upper limit on the number of tokens that can be remembered in each context.

  • Prompt (Turn 1)
    • Hi, what's the best place in Seattle to visit?
    • Response: The Columbia Center offers breathtaking views of the city skyline.
  • Prompt (Turn 2, continue interaction):
    • Will this be fun for children?
    • Response: No. There are much better places for children in Seattle.

 2.b.i Steps in Planning a Generative AI Project\textsf{\color{magenta} 2.b.i Steps in Planning a Generative AI Project} 2.b.i Steps in Planning a Generative AI Project

  •  Step 1: Define the scope\textsf{\color{cyan} Step 1: Define the scope} Step 1: Define the scope

  • What problem are you trying to solve?

  • What are the customer outcomes you wish to achieve?

  • Who are the target customers for your solution?

  • What are your internal governance or policy hurdles?

  • Where does funding for this solution come from?

  • What are your biggest technical or engineering challenges?

  • How will your customers repeatedly use the solution?

  • Who are the primary competitors to your solution?

  • Why will customers refer you to new customers?

  •  Step 2: Select a model\textsf{\color{cyan} Step 2: Select a model} Step 2: Select a model

The choice between using a pretrained model as is or fine-tuning a model for customization is primarily a trade-off between ease of use and flexibility.

  •  Step 3: Adapt model\textsf{\color{cyan} Step 3: Adapt model} Step 3: Adapt model

There are two ways you can customize the type of output you are getting from your models. Namely, prompt engineering and fine-tuning.

 2.c.i Risks and Mitigation\textsf{\color{magenta} 2.c.i Risks and Mitigation} 2.c.i Risks and Mitigation

  • Fairness
  • Privacy
  • Toxicity -> Curation of training data and Guardrail models
  • Hallucinations -> verification
  • Intellectual property -> Sharding, Filtering
  • Plagiarism and cheating
  • Disruption of the nature of work
Course - 3

 3. Amazon Bedrock Getting Started\textsf{\color{lime} 3. Amazon Bedrock Getting Started} 3. Amazon Bedrock Getting Started

 3.1.a. Introduction to Amazon Bedrock\textsf{\color{orange} 3.1.a. Introduction to Amazon Bedrock} 3.1.a. Introduction to Amazon Bedrock

Amazon Bedrock is a fully managed service that offers leading foundation models (FMs) and a set of capabilities to quickly build and scale generative artificial intelligence (generative AI) applications. The service also helps ensure privacy and security.

The capabilities of Amazon Bedrock include the following:

  • Foundation models that include a choice of base FMs and customized FMs
  • Playgrounds for chat, text, and images with quick access to FMs for experimentation and use through the console
  • Safeguards such as watermark detection and guardrails
  • Orchestration and automation for your application with knowledge bases and agents
  • Assessment and deployment with model evaluation and provisioned throughput

What are the three key benefits of Amazon Bedrock?

  • Efficiently build with FMs

    • Choose from various FMs
    • Access FMs through a single API
    • Take advantage of the fully managed experience

  • Securely build generative AI applications

    • Build with comprehensive data protection and privacy
    • Secure your generative AI applications
    • Access support for governance and auditability

  • Deliver customized experiences by using your organization’s data

    • Automate complex business tasks

    • Supplement organization-specific information to the FM

    • Fine-tune FMs by using Amazon Bedrock
